But it is right that the reader should know, that Mendoza has recorded some strong sentiments of his own, as well as two speeches delivered hy him on the occasion. He states that in the proposed decrees the monks were treated with less rigour, because they were employed in drawing up their own reformation. The nuns were dealt with less indulgently, on account of their general dissoluteness‚ of which the most formidable information reached the council, so much so, that the writer trembled at the thought of the judgments which, on account of such abominations (abomz‘nacz'ones)‚ appeared to have visited the church. He adds his sore grief, that in consequence of a great part of the scandal of the times being traceable to the licentiousness and profligacy of some bad religious, the reformation ran so much on penalties. Pesame mucho, que aviendo nacido gran parte de el escandalo de estos tempos de la licencia y perdicion de algunos malos Religiosos‚ se haga la Reformacion tau a sobre peine, y de manera que para los Hereges sera¹ risa, y para los catholicos muy poco edificacion. He speaks afterwards of tbe--mnchas llagas de Frailes y Monjas, que tienen harta necessidad de ser curadas : pero los frailes se dim tan buena maria, que podran poco o, haran que se remita el negocio de su reformacion a los Generales de las Ordenes, que es, quedarse las cosas como se estahan. Mnchos tienen de su parte, y creo que sun grangeardos. In the speeches of Mendoza immediately following, and which are of some extent, there is one passage which deserves attention sor its good sense, and some eonsequences, which the speaker perhaps did not contemplate. Of the canon respecting the age, eighteen years, at which profession of religion should be made, he expresses his approbation 3 and then adds—Longe etenim diversam ratio- nem esse arbitror eorum qui matrimonio junguntur, et illorum qui religionem profitentur, quia matrimonium remedium est concupiscentiae, religio perpetuum bellum gerit cum concupiscentia.
